 funded by significant debt and equity financing. For Q1 2026, the company cited:\n    *   **$17.95 billion** from the SpaceX Bridge Loan and other financing arrangements.\n    *   **$7.42 billion** from the sale of capital stock.\n*   **Future Outlook:** The company states it will "allocate substantial capital to build our AI compute infrastructure" and expects a **"multi-year investment horizon"** before these deployments turn consistently profitable (positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA).\n*   **Accounting:** Interest incurred during the construction of these data centers is capitalized. **$7 million** was capitalized in Q1 2026.\n\n---\n\n### **Supporting Financial Data**\n\n*   **Cash Flow from Investing Activities (Annual):**\n    *   2025: **$(19.575) billion** (Net cash used)\n    *   2024: $(10.796) billion\n    *   2023: $(4.867) billion\n*   **Property, Plant, and Equipment (Net Book Value):**\n    *   March 31, 2026: **$53.879 billion**\n    *   December 31, 2025: $42.602 billion\n    *   December 31, 2024: $21.147 billion\n\n### **Segment Context & Drivers**\n\n*   **Space Segment:** Capex driven by investment in **launch site infrastructure for the Starship program**.\n*   **Connectivity Segment (Starlink):** Capex driven by costs for **satellites and ground equipment** to grow the network.\n*   **AI Segment (acquired as xAI in Feb 2026):** Capex is for the **rapid expansion of terrestrial data centers** for AI compute. This is the most capital-intensive segment.\n\n### **xAI-Specific Mentions**\n\nWhile xAI is the entity acquired to form the AI segment, the filings do not list separate capex for "xAI." All capital expenditures for AI infrastructure are consolidated under the **"AI" segment** in the financial statements.',
